Bingley, Yorkshire, England","Combe Pyne, Devon, England":"Combe Pyne, Devon, England","Devon, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Shute (near Colyton), Devon, England":"Shute, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Pine  . This name has been established in Ireland since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Pine","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>pin(e)</i> (Old English <i>pīn</i>, Old French <i>pin</i>), a topographic name for someone who lived by a conspicuous pine tree or in a pine forest; in some cases it may originally have been a nickname for a tall man, one thought to resemble a pine tree.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>pine</i> ‘pain, injury, torture, punishment, infirmity’, referring to someone who suffered from an inflicted pain or punishment.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Le Pin in Calvados or some other French place called from a prominent pine."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":15,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":46,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Pyne was born about 1244, in Combe Pyne, Devon, England, his father, John De Pyne, was 21 and his mother, Hawise de Schete, was 35. He married Avis - Hawise De Shute in 1269, in Shute, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1293, in Bingley, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1244–1293":"umbes 1244–1293","1244–1293":"1244–1293","1248–1304":"1248–1304","1270–1295":"1270–1295","1224–1264":"1224–1264","1210–1304":"1210–1304","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","about 1244":"umbes 1244","14 May 1264":"14. mai 1264","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England","Bingley, Yorkshire, England":"Bingley, Yorkshire, England","Combe Pyne, Devon, England":"Combe Pyne, Devon, England","Devon, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Shute (near Colyton), Devon, England":"Shute, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1244–1293":"noin 1244–1293","